stylometry:
The variables we must consider are average rate of demand and average lead time, variability of demand and lead time, and the desired service level. Stock-out risk is also a component in determining service level.
Average rate of demand is what the average demand is for our product
Average lead time is the amount of time between orders.
Variabilty of demand and lead time is how much the demand and lead time can vary.
Service level is the percent chance our inventory will meet our demand.
we must know all these variables because safety stock is determined by knowing how much the demand can vary for our product during lead time. If therer is a high variability, then we should probably have more safety stock. If there is a low variability then we need less safety stock.
